The article discusses the effectiveness of a border wall in reducing illegal border crossings and crime in El Paso, Texas. It mentions that a two-story corrugated metal fence, similar to the one proposed by President Trump, was erected in 2006 and has significantly curtailed illegal crossings and crime in the city. The number of illegal crossings dropped from 122,261 in 2006 to 12,251 in 2010. The article also states that crime rates in El Paso decreased after the fence was built, making it one of the safest large cities in America. Additionally, drug smuggling along the border entry point has been cut in half since the fence was completed. The article concludes by mentioning that there is both empirical and anecdotal evidence supporting the idea that a southern border wall could be effective.